commit.message:
Fix support for Emacs < 27

- Fix call to setq-local which only supports 2 arguments in Emacs 26 and before.
- On Emacs < 27, setq-local does not support multiple (symbol value) argument pairs,
  it only supports one pair.  Since the package requirement specifies Emacs 24.3,
  it must also conforms to what was supported then.  Unfortunately Emacs 27 fails
  to describe that the argument signature differed before Emacs 27.

Clean up sections

Rename purely `macrostep'-function sections to be prefixed with "macrostep: ".

Remove spaces between page-break-lines and add section comments after each.

Subdivide the "Expansion: " section into back-ends and into the rest.

Support `cider'

Since there would be significant feature overlap between a cider-specific
`macrostep' package and `macrostep-geiser' (everything except for the string ->
expansion part).

To implement this, abstract away the expansion code into a buffer-locally set
expansion function: `macrostep-geiser-expand-function'. `macrostep-geiser-setup'
now `setq's it depending on whether `cider-mode' is enabled.

Fix misleading comment

Quotes are no longer removed; as such we no longer "unindented by a
space".

Support a non-autoloaded `macrostep'

`macrostep-geiser-expand-all' now requires `macrostep', to support set-ups where
autoloading does not work correctly.

No longer assume a quoted macroexpansion

The quoted macroexpansion result is a bug in geiser's racket REPL, and
not present in Guile. Now indent at newlines and no longer remove the
quote; the bug will have to be fixed upstream. As a consequence, other
REPL's now have correctly indented macroexpansions.

`expand-1': stricter whitespace handling

`macrostep-geiser-expand-1' now also considers the macro expansion the same, and
as such already fully expanded, if the resulting string and the original string
differ only in whitespace lengths: "(a b)" = "(a b)".

Forward declare `macrostep-expand'

`macrostep-expand' is autoloaded, so `declare'-ing it is safe. With it declared,
`macrostep-geiser' byte-compiles cleanly.

Add a new section for all declarations, and move the `defvar's to it.

READEME: add Usage section

The old Usage section becomes Set-up.

Add support for recursive expansion

If `macrostep-geiser-expand-all-mode' is enabled, `macrostep-geiser' will
recursively expand macros.

In addition, there is now a `macrostep-geiser-expand-all' command which will
call `macrostep' in a way that causes recursive expansion.
